Excercise 3: Semiparametric regression

Consider the data in https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/sameersmahajan/seattle-house-sales-prices. Price is your response variable y.

d=read.csv("datasets/house_sales.csv",header=TRUE)

Before fitting the model, let’s take a look at the dataset. It has 21613 observations across 21 variables:

  • id: Numeric identifier for each house sale.
  • date: Date of the sale in YYYY-MM-DD format.
  • price: Sale price of the house (in USD).
  • bedrooms: Number of bedrooms in the house.
  • bathrooms: Number of bathrooms in the house, including fractional values.
  • sqft_living: Square footage of the living space.
  • sqft_lot: Square footage of the lot.
  • floors: Number of floors in the house.
  • waterfront: Binary indicator of whether the house is waterfront (0 = No, 1 = Yes).
  • view: Binary indicator of whether the house has a view (0 = No, 1 = Yes).
  • condition: Condition of the house on a scale from 1 to 5.
  • grade: Grade of the house on a scale from 1 to 13.
  • sqft_above: Square footage of the house excluding the basement.
  • sqft_basement: Square footage of the basement.
  • yr_built: Year the house was built.
  • yr_renovated: Year the house was renovated (0 if not renovated).
  • zipcode: Zip code where the house is located.
  • lat: Latitude of the house’s location.
  • long: Longitude of the house’s location.
  • sqft_living15: Square footage of the living space in 2015.
  • sqft_lot15: Square footage of the lot in 2015.

The plots reveal several variables exhibiting skewness, including ‘price’ and ‘sqft_living.’ To address this, incorporating the log transformation of these variables into the model may improve its performance and interpretability.

Fit a semiparametric regression model

Model formula: \[ y_i = f(x_i) + \epsilon_i, \quad \epsilon_i \sim i.i.d. \, ~N(0, \sigma^2) \] Where:

  • \(y_i\) is the house price for observation \(i\);
  • \(x_i\) is sqft_living variable, so the square footage of the living area;
  • \(f(x_i)\) is a smooth function estimated from the data;
  • \(\epsilon_i\) are the error terms, assumed to be normally distributed with mean 0 and variance \(\sigma^2\).

Before fitting the model, we can look at the data distributions of the predictor and the response and their correlation: 

## [1] "The correlation between the variables is 0.702035052433682"

As we can see, the 2 variables are higly correlated. Therefore, the spline model might be a good fit for the data.

model <- gam(price ~ s(sqft_living), data = d)

Discuss the model fit, explain why the model is not adequate and propose how to improve it.

The model summary indicates that ‘sqft_living’ is a significant predictor of house price. However, the model explains only 55% of the variance, suggesting that incorporating additional covariates could improve its predictive power.

Then, by looking at the residuals plots, we can notice that: 

##

  • the QQ Plot indicates non-normality of the residuals;
  • the Resids vs Fitted Plot suggests the presence of patterns in the residuals that were not adequately captured by the model;
  • the Response vs Fitted Plot reveals heteroscedasticity, with the residuals exhibiting greater variability for larger fitted values.

Further consideration on the datset and EDA:

To enhance the model’s performance, we will incorporate additional covariates and consider transformations for both the response variable and predictors. Therefore, the following variables will be log-transformed for subsequent analyses:

Now that we have transformed these variables, we can drop the non transformed versions:

# Drop the non-transformed variables:
d <- d[, !grepl("^sqft_living$|^price$|^sqft_lot$|^view$|^sqft_above$|^sqft_basement$|^sqft_living15$|^sqft_lot15$", names(d))]
colnames(d)

An examination of the heatmap reveals correlations among certain predictor variables. To address potential multicollinearity issues, we will re-examine the heatmap without the target variable. Predictors exhibiting high correlations will not be simultaneously included in the models.

Then, another important factor to consider is the location of the house:

From the maps above, we can see that there are some city areas where the prices are significantly higher. These price variations emphasize the significant influence of location on housing values. Consequently, incorporating spatial variables into the model may be essential for a more accurate representation of the housing market.

Fitting better models:

Splitting the dataset in train and test

Before fitting the model and to be able to asses the capacities of the models in predicting new data, we need to split the dataset in train and test:

# dividing the data into training and test sets:
set.seed(42)
train_indices <- sample(1:nrow(d), 0.8 * nrow(d))
train_data <- d[train_indices,]
test_data <- d[-train_indices,]

Models fitting

We can start by fitting a model with the most correlated variables with the target variable, while excluding highly correlated predictor pairs:

model_hc <- gam(log_price ~ s(log_sqft_living15) + s(bedrooms) + s(log_sqft_basement) + factor(waterfront) + s(log_sqft_lot), data = train_data)
# not considering s(floors) and s(log_view) because they have fewer unique covariate combinations than specified maximum degrees of freedom

Another approach would be to incorporate information about the house location, in addition to log_sqft_living.

  • with the coordinates te(lat, long):
model_coordinates <- gam(log_price ~ s(log_sqft_living) + te(lat, long), data = train_data)
  • with zipcode as a factor:
model_zipcode <- gam(log_price ~ s(log_sqft_living) + factor(zipcode), data = train_data)

We may even combine these 2 strategies with a balanced model:

model_mixed_strategies <- gam(log_price ~ s(log_sqft_living) + factor(zipcode) + s(bedrooms) + factor(waterfront), data = train_data)

Predictive efficacy:

To understand how well the models perform, we can calculate the Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE) and Mean Absolute Error (MAE) on the test data:

We can also plot the predicted vs actual values and the residuals for each model:

Overall, the best choice would be model_zipcode, because:

  • it is a good compromise between a simple and understandable model and a low GCV (Generalized Cross-Validation) score;
  • it has low RMSE and MAE values on the test data;
  • it has a good predictive efficacy, as shown by the predicted vs actual values and residuals plots.

Devise a model to assess whether there is any seasonality in the price.

To investigate potential seasonality in prices, we can include variables representing the month and quarter of the year in which the sales occurred.

The first step is to extract the month or quarter to analyze seasonal trends:

##         date month quarter
## 1 2014-10-13    10       4
## 2 2014-12-09    12       4
## 3 2015-02-25     2       1
## 4 2014-12-09    12       4
## 5 2015-02-18     2       1
## 6 2014-05-12     5       2

Then, we can check any seasonal patterns in the data by plotting the boxplots of the price distribution by month and quarter:

We can also print the anova values for the monthly and quarterly price differences:

# ANOVA for Monthly Price Differences
anova_month_result <- aov(log_price ~ factor(month), data = d)
summary(anova_month_result)
##                  Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value   Pr(>F)    
## factor(month)    11     18  1.6007   5.784 2.02e-09 ***
## Residuals     21601   5977  0.2767                     
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
# ANOVA for Quarterly Price Differences
anova_quarter_result <- aov(log_price ~ factor(quarter), data = d)
summary(anova_quarter_result)
##                    Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value   Pr(>F)    
## factor(quarter)     3     12   4.100   14.81 1.25e-09 ***
## Residuals       21609   5983   0.277                     
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Both summaries indicate that both month and quarter have a significant effect on the response variable. This means that the average value of the response variable differs significantly across the different months and quarters.

However, 4 quarters are too few to fit a spline model, so we can only fit the model for the months.

Hence, we can consider the average log_price for each month:

# Dataframe with month and the average log_price for each month
df_month <- d %>%
  group_by(month) %>%
  summarise(avg_log_price = mean(log_price, na.rm = TRUE))

And fit a spline model:

model_month <- gam(avg_log_price ~ s(month), data = df_month)
